=== Discovered PowerShell JSON-parsing quirk (fixed inside this task's own
file; not a Specification Difference against the .sh original's BEHAVIOR,
only against a literal jq-vs-ConvertFrom-Json type-system difference) ===

During the round-2/round-3 drive above, `Test-ValidateContract`'s
own-stage prior-round re-validation (the PowerShell translation of
`validate_contract()`/`validate_reviewer_output()`, `spec-review-precheck.sh`
lines 85-195) initially failed at the final `integrated-summary.json`
`generated_at` field check. Root cause, isolated via an instrumented copy of
the function running against the real loop-driver-produced fixture (see
Working Notes in the implementation report): PowerShell 7's
`ConvertFrom-Json` auto-coerces ISO-8601-looking JSON STRING values (e.g.
`"generated_at": "2026-06-23T00:00:00Z"`) into `[DateTime]` objects, unlike
`jq`, which never performs implicit type coercion and always sees a JSON
string as a string. The original PowerShell translation of the .sh
original's `(.generated_at | type == "string")` check
(`$summary.generated_at -isnot [string]`) was therefore too strict for this
one field under PS7's parser. Fixed by adding a `Test-IsStringLike` helper
(`($Value -is [string]) -or ($Value -is [DateTime])`) and using it only at
that one call site -- the underlying JSON value IS a string in every case
(a `[DateTime]` result is proof the source WAS a string, since only actual
JSON strings are eligible for this coercion), so this preserves the
original's semantic intent (the field exists and is a well-formed
timestamp-shaped value) while accommodating PS7's parser behavior. Verified
with `-AsHashtable` too: the coercion happens regardless of
`ConvertFrom-Json`'s output-object mode, so no alternate parsing flag avoids
it. No other field in this task's port holds a value that PS7 could
similarly misclassify (sha256 hex digests, feature slugs, role/schema
names, and UUIDs do not parse as dates).

